This is the R markdown (rmd) exercise file that accompanies the lecture notes. It will be your sandbox! Fill in the R code chunks, experiment, and have fun!

Importing Data

Import from csv file

Download the data of the stock of your choice from Yahoo Finance, and read it in using read.csv():

data_csv=read.csv("DWAC.csv",header=TRUE)

Importatn note: when downloading the data, right click the download link and “save link as” to save to file to the same folder as your rmd file. If you open the csv file in Excel, do NOT save it or “save as”, because doing so will will mess up the csv date format, and you will encounter error in converting the date column in a later exercise. If that happens, you need to download the csv file again.

Converting Data Frame to XTS

Convert your data frame to xts:

library(xts)
## Loading required package: zoo

## Attaching package: 'zoo'

stockdata_csv=xts(
  xts(data_csv[ ,2:7], order.by=data_csv[ ,1])
  
)

Technical Indicators

Simple Moving Average (SMA)

Simple Moving Average (SMA)

Readings on SMA: https://www.fidelity.com/learning-center/trading-investing/technical-analysis/technical-indicator-guide/sma

SMA Example

Calculate SMA

Calculate the 50-day moving average for your stock:

x=Cl(stock_data2)
head(x)
##            MSFT.Close
## 2010-12-31      27.91
## 2011-01-03      27.98
## 2011-01-04      28.09
## 2011-01-05      28.00
## 2011-01-06      28.82
## 2011-01-07      28.60
names(x)="close"
x$sma=rollmeanr(x$close,k=50)

Another function that calculates the rolling mean is the rollmean() function. Can you find out difference between rollmean() and rollmeanr()?

d=rollmean(x$close,k=50)

## 2010-12-31 27.91  NA

## 2011-01-04 28.09  NA
## 2011-01-05 28.00  NA
## 2011-01-06 28.82  NA
## 2011-01-07 28.60  NA

In a spreadsheet, how would you calculate the moving average?

Plot the SMA

Make a plot of the SMA:

plot(x,legend.loc="topleft")

Make it a function!

Turn the SMA code into a function:

mysma=function(stock_data2){
    x=Cl(stock_data2)
    names(x)="close"
    x$sma=rollmeanr(x$close,k=50)
    retun=(x$sma)
}

Test the function

Test your function to see if it can generate the same plot:

plot(mysma(stock_data2))

Make it a flexible function

Make your function more flexible so that it can generate SMA of different window lengths:

mysma=function(stock_data2,k){
    x=Cl(stock_data2)
    names(x)="close"
    x$sma=rollmeanr(x$close,k=50)
    retun=(x$sma)
}

Test the flexible function

Test the flexible SMA function to generate a 200-day SMA:

mysma(stock_data2,k=10)
plot(stock_data2,k=10)

SMA Crossing

Plot the 50-day and 200-day SMA on the same figure.

data_to_plot=cbind(
  Cl(stock_data2),
  mysma(stock_data2,k=50),
  mysma(stock_data2,k=200)
)
plot(data_to_plot,legend.loc="topleft")

Relative Strength Indicator (RSI)

RSI Definition

Learn about RSI:

http://stockcharts.com/school/doku.php?id=chart_school:technical_indicators:relative_strength_index_rsi

https://www.fidelity.com/learning-center/trading-investing/technical-analysis/technical-indicator-guide/RSI

RSI Example

Clifford Ang’s text (Chapte 1) talks about how to create the RSI technical indicator. Let’s implement it in R here.

RSI Calculation 1

Select the closing price, calculate the change in price for up days and down days:

z=Cl(stock_data2)
names(z)="price"
z$delta=diff(z$price)
z$up=ifelse(z$delta>0,1,0)
z$dw=ifelse(z$delta<0,1,0)
z$up.val=z$delta*z$up
z$dw.val=z$delta*z$dw

RSI Calculation 2

Calculate the rolling average gain and average loss:

z$up.avg=NA
z$up.avg[15]=mean(z$up.val[2:15])
z$dw.avg=NA
z$dw.avg[15]=mean(z$dw.val[2:15])
for(i in 16:nrow(z)){
z$up.avg[i]=(as.numeric(z$up.avg[i-1])*13+as.numeric(z$up.val[i])*1)/14
z$dw.avg[i]=(as.numeric(z$dw.avg[i-1])*13+as.numeric(z$dw.val[i])*1)/14
}

Make it a function!

Collect the code for RSI calculation into a function. The function takes a price series as input, and return a time series of RSI. Make the funtion more flexible by allowing the user to choose parameter n (default to be 14) for the number of periods for moving averages.

myRSI=function(stock_data2){
  

z=Cl(stock_data2)
names(z)="price"

z$delta=diff(z$price)

z$up=ifelse(z$delta>0,1,0)
z$dw=ifelse(z$delta<0,1,0)


z$up.val=z$delta*z$up
z$dw.val=z$delta*z$dw

z$up.avg=NA
z$up.avg[15]=mean(z$up.val[2:15])
z$dw.avg=NA
z$dw.avg[15]=mean(z$dw.val[2:15])

for(i in 16:nrow(z)){
z$up.avg[i]=(as.numeric(z$up.avg[i-1])*13+as.numeric(z$up.val[i])*1)/14
z$dw.avg[i]=(as.numeric(z$dw.avg[i-1])*13+as.numeric(z$dw.val[i])*1)/14
}

z$RS=z$up.avg/z$dw.avg

z$RSI=100-100/(1+z$RS)

return(z$RSI)
}

Later we will see how one can use a custom function like this one in constructing trading strategy for backtesting!

Test the function
